{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652278"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:34:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:34:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18528"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18528"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11257"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79711"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11257"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18528"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65015"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10793"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26101"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79711"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA laboratory report describes a genetic change in the BRCA1 gene. The change involves a single DNA base, where cytosine (C) is replaced by thymine (T). This creates a stop signal in the protein sequence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the correct way to write this genetic change according to the Human Genome Variation Society nomenclature guidelines?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["BRCA1 mutation C to T","BRCA1 stop mutation","BRCA1 DNA change","BRCA1 c.181C\u003ET, p.Gln61*","BRCA1 variant detected"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct format \u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA1 c.181C\u003ET, p.Gln61*\u003C/strong\u003E follows the standardised Human Genome Variation Society (HGVS) nomenclature guidelines. This format includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGene name (BRCA1)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECoding DNA reference sequence (c.)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPosition of the variant (181)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EChange at DNA level (C\u003ET)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPredicted protein change (p.Gln61*)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are inadequate because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA1 mutation C to T\u003C/strong\u003E lacks proper formatting and position information\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA1 stop mutation\u003C/strong\u003E is too vague and does not specify the location or exact change\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA1 DNA change\u003C/strong\u003E provides no specific information about the variant\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRCA1 variant detected\u003C/strong\u003E is non-specific and lacks essential details\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStandardised nomenclature is essential for clear communication of genetic variants between laboratories and healthcare providers to prevent misinterpretation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Genetic test results should be communicated using standardised nomenclature from the Human Genome Variation Society (HGVS).","Pathogenic variants should be described at both DNA and protein levels when reporting genetic test results.","Reference sequences must be included when reporting genetic test results to ensure unambiguous interpretation."],"references":["Hart RK, Fokkema IFAC, DiStefano M, Hastings R, Laros JFJ, Taylor R, et al. HGVS Nomenclature 2024: improvements to community engagement, usability, and computability. Genome Medicine. 2024;16(1):149. Available at: https://genomemedicine.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13073-024-01421-5"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65015"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18528"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65015"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T13:18:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T13:36:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11257"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79711"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4945"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11